<p>With artificial intelligence becoming a popular and integral part of retail operations, apparel brands are on the lookout for the right technology. This guide explores AI's growing role in retail, and how it helps apparel brands increase efficiency, enhance personalization, and make effective forecasts.</p>

<h2>The current state of apparel retail</h2>
<p>The apparel industry is experiencing several changes. Consumer expectations are evolving faster than ever, and the traditional boundaries between online and offline retail have all but disappeared. Today, customers expect to browse on their phones, check stock in-store, order online, and return anywhere, all while enjoying convenient, tailored, and consistent shopping experiences.</p>
<p>AI is helping retailers live up to changing consumer expectations. Once seen as an emerging technology, AI has now become a critical part of retail ecosystems. From smarter checkouts to personalized style recommendations, the right AI tools let brands deliver frictionless, data-driven, customer-centric shopping experiences. It isn't about replacing human staff with AI, it's about empowering them to perform their tasks efficiently and effectively.</p>
<p>According to a 2025 Statista survey, retailers' top AI investment priorities for 2025 are sales and marketing (33%) and product support (31%). At Teamwork Commerce, we believe AI is the natural evolution of retail intelligence. Teamwork Commerce partnered with Google Cloud to develop new generative AI features in its Mobile Point of Sale (POS) and Order Management System (OMS), aiming to bring a fusion of Teamwork's retail solutions with Google Cloud's generative AI capabilities for enterprise retail organizations.</p>
<p>As a result, Teamwork Commerce will be able to equip store associates with mobile devices with a generative AI assistant specifically trained to help with inventory questions, allowing staff to quickly check backroom stock or other locations for specific customer requests.</p>

<h2>The omnichannel imperative in apparel</h2>
<p>Apparel retail has always been about connection between brand and consumer, trend and identity, experience and emotion. Those connections have now become hybrid. Shoppers want to browse online, try in-store, and buy wherever they feel most comfortable.</p>
<p>Omnichannel isn't optional anymore, it's becoming a common retail expectation. Apparel shoppers often engage with more than one channel before purchasing, yet many retailers still struggle with siloed systems and fragmented data that make consistency difficult. Within an integrated retail ecosystem, AI can draw insights from one area of the business and apply them to enhance another, connecting operations, sales, and customer engagement into a unified loop of intelligence.</p>

<h2>AI in POS: the intelligent storefront</h2>
<p>The point of sale is no longer just a transaction point; it's a critical last touchpoint that retailers can use to ensure a top-tier customer experience while collecting crucial data. AI-driven POS solutions can deliver:</p>
<ul>
<li>Predictive capabilities, empowering associates to provide personalized promotions or product recommendations in real time</li>
<li>Integrated loyalty and personalization engines that connect purchase history with customer profiles, so retailers recognize shoppers instantly both offline and online</li>
<li>Dynamic pricing and upsell recommendations driven by data insights, so offers stay relevant and timely</li>
</ul>
<p>With an AI-powered connected retail stack integrated with loyalty engines, associates can scan an item and instantly see complimentary items or personalized discounts based on a customer's purchase history, preferences, and recent online browsing, turning a transactional POS moment into a personalized shopping journey. AI-enabled POS can also automate routine tasks like inventory updates and receipt processing, minimizing checkout queues.</p>

<h2>RFID and AI-powered self-checkout</h2>
<p>Fashion retailers face a unique challenge: multiple SKUs, varied sizes, and complex transactions. Traditional self-checkout systems struggle with this complexity, since each item requires manual scanning, which is slow and prone to error. RFID-powered self-checkout kiosks address this by automating the entire scanning process, letting customers accurately scan multiple items in seconds. Brought together, AI and RFID make self-checkout seamless and efficient.</p>
<p>With Teamwork Commerce's RFID-Powered Self-Checkout solution, retailers can:</p>
<ul>
<li>Automate the checkout process, freeing staff time for higher-value tasks like personalizing interactions</li>
<li>Minimize losses and theft, since the solution can trigger alarms if products are removed from the basket without being paid for</li>
<li>Integrate seamless payments, including digital payment, loyalty points, and split payments through a unified interface</li>
<li>Let customers choose self-checkout or a human-led counter</li>
</ul>

<h2>AI-enhanced OMS: the driver of omnichannel fulfillment</h2>
<p>Behind every smooth customer journey is a powerful order management system. For apparel retailers managing hundreds of SKUs across multiple locations, the complexity can be overwhelming. Teamwork Commerce's omnichannel Order Management System operates in real time, giving retailers visibility across all shopping channels and integrating with POS and CRM platforms for a consistent experience. The OMS is also integrated with inventory management in real time, so brands can automatically reroute orders if a product goes out of stock or demand spikes unexpectedly.</p>
<p>When the OMS receives an order confirmation, its order fill logic creates a ship memo based on the allocated primary location, enabling real-time data flow and accuracy. Orders can be fulfilled to the customer's preferred location with ease, and integrations with leading 3PLs streamline fulfillment directly from the POS. The OMS can also determine the most efficient source for each order, whether ship-from-store, buy online pickup in store, or endless aisle, based on delivery time, inventory levels, and shipping cost, automatically and within seconds.</p>

<h2>Personalization in apparel</h2>
<p>Fashion is subjective and deeply personal. Customers seek confidence, fit, and identity, not just clothes. AI enables personalization at a scale that was once impossible. Leading apparel brands today use AI to:</p>
<ul>
<li>Make style and size recommendations based on past purchases, browsing behavior, and even climate patterns</li>
<li>Facilitate virtual try-ons powered by computer vision and AR</li>
<li>Roll out virtual assistants for instant style advice or post-purchase support</li>
</ul>
<p>Teamwork Commerce's technology stack integrates these capabilities across every touchpoint, whether an in-store associate's tablet, an online storefront, or a mobile app, so the customer experience stays consistent, intelligent, and brand-aligned.</p>

<h2>Supply chain and inventory optimization</h2>
<p>Apparel retailers often struggle with overstocking, markdowns, and unpredictable demand. AI's predictive capabilities help retailers forecast demand by analyzing sales trends, weather, social media sentiment, and local events, optimize replenishment cycles, and minimize waste and overproduction. Teamwork Commerce's Reporting and Analytics platform gives apparel retailers visibility into sales and inventory in one place, with real-time dashboards and demand predictions based on historical data. Meanwhile, the OMS can automatically adjust fulfillment routes or reallocate stock between stores when a trend begins to spike, leading to leaner operations, reduced markdowns, and improved environmental impact.</p>

<h2>The future of AI in apparel retail</h2>
<p>The future of AI in apparel retail will be defined by hyper-personalization and predictive omnichannel journeys: AI tools that predict when a loyal shopper is likely to buy again and proactively curate a capsule wardrobe, smart mirrors that recognize returning shoppers and recommend outfits based on online browsing, and inventory systems that automatically sync with marketing campaigns to keep in-demand products available. Apparel retailers who treat AI as a continuous capability, not a one-off project, will stay ahead of those who don't.</p>

<h2>Conclusion</h2>
<p>AI is changing the way apparel retailers operate, enabling frictionless shopping, real-time inventory control, personalized engagement, and sustainable growth. But technology alone isn't enough without valuable partnerships and strategic execution. Teamwork Commerce works closely with apparel retailers as a partner, deploying integrated solutions that function in real time. From Lucchese and Asics to Moose Knuckles and FAO Schwarz, Teamwork Commerce helps top-tier players deliver high-quality customer experiences with optimal efficiency.</p>
